abstract: Updates from around the country as candidates make their final pitches to the voters who will help reshape America for the next two years.
snippet: Updates from around the country as candidates make their final pitches to the voters who will help reshape America for the next two years.
lead_paragraph: New York Times journalists are reporting from around the country this weekend as candidates make their final pitches to the voters who will help reshape the United States for the next two years.

abstract: Ahead of the midterm elections, we asked young evangelicals to tell The Times about the relationship between their faith and their politics.
snippet: Ahead of the midterm elections, we asked young evangelicals to tell The Times about the relationship between their faith and their politics.
lead_paragraph: The role of evangelical Christianity in American politics has been a hotly discussed topic this year, intersecting with front-burner issues like immigration, the Supreme Court and social justice. Often the loudest evangelical voices are white, male and … not young.

abstract: Fighting for their political lives, they have given little thought to an agenda should they hold onto power. But a few items are clear: more tax cuts, less spending and a bull’s-eye on Obamacare.
snippet: Fighting for their political lives, they have given little thought to an agenda should they hold onto power. But a few items are clear: more tax cuts, less spending and a bull’s-eye on Obamacare.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — House Republicans, fighting hard to retain their majority and uncertain about who will lead them after Tuesday’s elections, have deferred the messy work of planning a legislative agenda until after the votes are tallied next week.

lead_paragraph: ESTERO, Fla. — With a somber trip to Pittsburgh to visit victims of a synagogue shooting behind him, President Trump flew to one of his favorite places in the world — Florida — on Wednesday to host another one of his high-decibel political rallies.

abstract: As a Legal Aid lawyer, she won a suit to protect inmates who faced reprisals from guards after the deadly 1971 prison uprising. She later became a judge.
snippet: As a Legal Aid lawyer, she won a suit to protect inmates who faced reprisals from guards after the deadly 1971 prison uprising. She later became a judge.
lead_paragraph: Phylis Skloot Bamberger, a lawyer who successfully sued to protect inmates from what a federal judge described as “barbarous abuse” by guards in the wake of the 1971 Attica prison uprising, died on Sunday at her home in Manhattan. She was 79.

abstract: For two years, the pseudonymous literary sensation corresponded regularly with the director adapting “My Brilliant Friend” for HBO. But the resulting show is a testament to her elusiveness.
snippet: For two years, the pseudonymous literary sensation corresponded regularly with the director adapting “My Brilliant Friend” for HBO. But the resulting show is a testament to her elusiveness.
lead_paragraph: Saverio Costanzo, the 43-year-old director of the HBO limited series “My Brilliant Friend,” is a haunted man. For over a decade, he has corresponded with a woman whose face he cannot see, whose voice he cannot hear, whose existence is confirmed only by the many thousands of words she has written dissecting his artistic choices. When he speaks of her, his black eyes turn upward, as if seeking a trace of her in the cracks of the ceiling or in some metaphysical plane high above the penthouse suite of the Beverly Hilton Hotel, where Costanzo and the cast of “My Brilliant Friend” have arrived for HBO’s summer press tour. “Sometimes she was so strong,” he said, gruffly. “I don’t know. I’m still trying to put everything together. It’s very hard. It was like working with a ghost.”

abstract: “What can you show us that might help make the portrait of ‘Gen Z’ more interesting, nuanced, complete or real?” we asked. Nearly 2,200 students answered.

lead_paragraph: Back in September, we challenged teenagers to analyze media and adult stereotypes about their generation — then take photos to counter them.

abstract: Our approach is specific to black Southerners. But our model can work for anyone.
snippet: Our approach is specific to black Southerners. But our model can work for anyone.
lead_paragraph: This month, we got on a bus with some colleagues and made our way to a senior center in Louisville, Ga., a quaint town about 50 miles from Augusta. The trip was part of a bus tour across the South to talk to black people about building political power.

abstract: Tampa Bay’s surprising 90-win season and its history of innovation has made its employees attractive to other teams. Two of them became managers this week.
snippet: Tampa Bay’s surprising 90-win season and its history of innovation has made its employees attractive to other teams. Two of them became managers this week.
lead_paragraph: LOS ANGELES — When Nathan Eovaldi joined the Boston Red Sox this summer, his old team was a source of curiosity in his new clubhouse. Eovaldi had pitched for the Tampa Bay Rays, baseball’s most innovative think tank. The Rays did not reach the playoffs, but their surprise 90-win season commanded attention.
